<subSubSection type="nomenclature">
<paragraph pageNumber="214">
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:139202" authority="Mayr, 1861" authorityName="Mayr" authorityYear="1861" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Acantholepis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName-HNS="Acantholepis capensis var. anceps Forel" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="214" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="variety" species="capensis" variety="anceps">Acantholepis capensis Mayr variety anceps Forel</taxonomicName>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="materials_examined">
<paragraph pageNumber="214">
Stanleyville, [[worker]]; Medje, [[worker]] (Lang and Chapin). Numerous specimens. This variety is close to the subspecies depilis, having sparse, short, whitish pilosity. In shape the epinotum and scale, as Forel remarks, approach those of the 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:237267" authority="Mayr, 1861" authorityName="Mayr" authorityYear="1861" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Acantholepis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName-HNS="Acantholepis capensis subsp. simplex Forel" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="214" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subSpecies" species="capensis" subSpecies="simplex">subspecies simplex</taxonomicName>
Forel. The variety was originally described from specimens taken by Kohl in the Belgian Congo, probably near Stanleyville. According to a note by Mr. Lang, this ant makes tiny craters in the soil after the rain. The colonies seem to be rather small, judging from the few workers seen outside the nests.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="description">
<paragraph pageNumber="214">
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:139203" authority="Mayr, 1861" authorityName="Mayr" authorityYear="1861" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Acantholepis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName-HNS="Acantholepis capensis var. guineensis Mayr" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="214" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="variety" species="capensis" variety="guineensis">Acantholepis capensis variety guineensis Mayr</taxonomicName>
A single worker from Thysville (Lang and Chapin) appears to belong to this variety, which is not black, like the other forms of the species, but reddish brown. The hairs are yellowish. It was originally described from the Gold Coast.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
